node.title: Error in rebuild Libmesh after reseting MOOSE to old version
node.bodyText:
Hi all,
I have successfully installed MOOSE according to the tutorial of the following website：
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/getting_started/installation/conda.html
However, for some reason, i have to reset moose to old version, for example, the 2021 version (commit 25abc3b). So i run the following command:
cd ~/projects/moose
git reset --hard 25abc3b
git clean -xfd

And then clean the previous compilation:
cd ~/projects/moose/test
make clobberall

After that, i try to rebuild libmesh:
cd ~/projects/moose
./scripts/update_and_rebuild_libmesh.sh

However, it show errors finally :

here is the
libmesh_diagnostic.log
Please help to resolve the problem, thanks!

Part of the issue is, that you have install moose-libmesh (as denoted by the environment variable):
LIBMESH_DIR=/home/dcq/mambaforge3/envs/moose/libmesh

Yet you are also trying to install your own via the ./update_and_rebubild_libmesh.sh script. While this should work by completely overwriting what was installed by conda, you should refrain from doing so. I suggest you do the following:
Delete the current 'moose' environment, and start over, and not attempting to run ./update_and_rebuild_libmesh.sh
mamba activate base
mamba env remove -n moose
mamba create -n moose moose-tools moose-libmesh
mamba activate moose
cd ~/projects/moose
git clean -xfd
git submodule foreach --recursive git clean -xfd
cd test
make -j4
./run_tests -j 4
And continue with your end goal (building your own App, etc using Stork, etc)
@milljm Thank you. I will try according to your advice.

Hello
A negative Jacobian would mean an element got deformed enough to be inverted.
Your mesh is really coarse and your time steps are pretty large. Could you please check if those parameters are the issue?

The convergence issue here is caused by an inappropriate choice of the path following algorithm.
The load displacement curve of a plastic material typically looks like this

In your input file you are using a Neumann BC to "follow" this curve, which is equivalent to prescribing the y component of this curve. It is apparent that no solution exist pass the ultimate strength. Numerically, this relates to non-convergence with many inverted elements. You are essentially asking the model to perform an impossible task.
In this case, you'll have to change the path following algorithm to a displacement-controlled one. That is changing the Neumann BC to a Dirichlet BC. You can add a postprocessor to output the force:

  []
[]

    variable = fz
    boundary = front
  []
[]
You'll see that the force starts decreasing after certain point, and that corresponds to the point at which Neumann BC fails.

node.title: Using TabulatedFluidProperties with FlowChannel1Phase
node.bodyText:
Hello all,
Hopefully this is a simple fix: I'm attempting to build a simulation that uses many components from the Thermal Hydraulics module include the FlowChannel1Phase. In addition, I have some flow properties that I have saved in a CSV file (completely separate from MOOSE) that I would like to use instead of an IdealGasFluidProperties object.
As soon as I set everything up and run, I get this error:
*** ERROR ***
The following error occurred in the object "tabulated_fluid_data", of type "TabulatedFluidProperties".

tabulated_fluid_data: virtual libMesh::Real SinglePhaseFluidProperties::e_from_p_rho(libMesh::Real, libMesh::Real) const not implemented.

Here is the portion of the input file where I set up my fluid properties:
[Modules]
  [./FluidProperties]
    [./original]
                       type = IdealGasFluidProperties
			gamma = 1.3845
			k = 0.19158
			molar_mass = 0.00201588
			mu = 8.9154e-5
    [../]
    [./tabulated_fluid_data]
			type = TabulatedFluidProperties
			fluid_property_file = fluid_properties.csv
			fp = original
			pressure_min = 1
			pressure_max = 100000000
			temperature_min = 1
			temperature_max = 6000
     []
   []
[]

And here's my flow channel component:
[fch]
		type = FlowChannel1Phase
		position = '0 0 0'
		orientation = '0 0 1'
		fp = tabulated_fluid_data
		n_elems = 6
		length = ${L}
		initial_T = 1000
		initial_p = 2.3e6
		initial_vel = 0
		closures = simple_closures
		A = 0.000005309
		f = 0
[]

Is it possible to load in this custom fluid properties data? and if so, how?
Many thanks ahead of time!
EDIT: Sorry for the terribly formatted code, my IDE did not like that copy and paste for some reason.

Hello
It is possible in a pull request, but not in the current version of MOOSE. @spaubt2  and I are actively working on making this work.
e_from_p_rho is currently not implemented for this fluid property in MOOSE, but we have it working well in this pull request
#21301
@spaubt2 can you please upload the latest working version to the PR so @jcstonehillAMA may try it
Guillaume
